    value: 'Silver Hooks (銀鉤): A reference to exceptionally strong and forceful calligraphy, particularly the cursive script of the Jin dynasty master Su Jing, which was celebrated as possessing ''silver hooks and scorpion tails.'''
  - key: ''
    value: 'Mending Heaven (補天): An allusion to the mythological Nüwa who patched the sky with five-colored stones. Used metaphorically to refer to restoring the fortune of the realm.'
  - key: ''
    value: 'Supporting the Sun (捧日): An expression of loyal support for the ruler, based on ancient metaphors comparing the sun to the king.'
  - key: ''
    value: 'Eight Layers Deep (八分): Likely a reference to the famous saying about Wang Xizhi''s calligraphy penetrating three layers into wood, here transformed to emphasize extraordinary skill.'
  - key: ''
    value: 'The Lanting manuscript: The most celebrated work of Wang Xizhi, often considered the pinnacle of Chinese calligraphy.'
  - key: ''
    value: 'The Blessed Isles (蓬萊山): The mythical island home of immortals, implying the work is so fine it rivals celestial treasures.'
  - key: ''
    value: 'Queque (闕黨): The village where Confucius lived, used here to represent even the greatest disciples of the sage.'
